summary: Why Arthritis pain increase in Winter
title: Why Arthritis pain increase in Winter
body: Why Arthritis pain increase in Winter . For many Arthritis patients, pain, swelling, stiffness, fatigue and other common rheumatoid arthritis symptoms are harder to control during the winter. Some people feel more joint pain, for example, when the weather turns cold and dam temperatures, icy sidewalks and holiday stress can be even more challenging when you’re dealing with rheumatoid arthritis symptoms.

12.26.18 - The first of many Weigh-In Wednesdays: 275.6
So as much as I didn’t want to weigh in today knowing how horrible the...
body:
12.26.18 - The first of many Weigh-In Wednesdays: 275.6


So as much as I didn’t want to weigh in today knowing how horrible the past few days (and weeks) have been, I did it. I put off the “I can do it Friday or at the beginning of the year” thing and remembered that I need to stop making excuses, new timelines, and just DO IT.


The first thing I am really focusing on is getting back to Keto. I didn’t lose a ton of weight doing it (but, I mean, to be fair I wasn’t exactly strict enough about it anyway) but damn, ever since I have stopped I feel like CRAP. My face is acting up again, my body doesn’t feel as good. So yeah, I know that regardless of the weight loss, it is a diet that makes my body feel good. I think seeing that difference makes it a lifestyle change I am 110% committed to. I still probably won’t be as strict as some people are, especially in the beginning because we have a few things hanging around, but I certainly cannot deal with how crappy I feel NOT eating that way. So 🤷‍♀️


Right now the challenge for me is that I twisted my ankle last week. So that makes the workout aspect of it a little tricky. But I am going to really hone in on my diet.


As much as I have said this a million times, I am really going to try to post here and use this as accountability and motivation. I did so well when I was sharing my journey on here all those years ago. I am going to use that to fuel me.


Aanyway, I had to sleep in a bit because of my ankle waking me up in the middle of the night. So I have to get ready and dash down to work.


Hope you all have a fantastic day!

summary: Getting a lot of stiffness in lower back when finishing certain lifts via /r/Fitness
title: Getting a lot of stiffness in lower back when finishing certain lifts via /r/Fitness
body:
I run GZCLP and I’ve been really enjoying it, however I noticed that the tier 2 (3x10) deadlifts are super taxing on my lower back. It’s not really pain, it just feels super stiff after I finish the lift. Once I get home it’s always gone though, but it’s definitely not enjoyable when I’m still working out, and I usually need a minute or so to just sit down/rest for my back once I finish my deadlifts.

I also noticed this during the 3x10 squats, my lower back will start to get stiff, but not as bad as the deadlifts though. I recently started doing rack pulls above the knee, and there too once I finish I start feeling the stiffness in my lowerback.

I want to fix this but I’m not sure what it is, is it because of form, (Which I feel isn’t it, since I pay very close attention to my form on both squats and deadlift) is my lower back just too weak or do I need to start doing certain stretches?

I’m 191cm/6’3 @ 73kg/161lbs

My lifts are:

T1 Squat: 95kg/209lbs (3x5)

T2 Squat: 67,5kg/149lbs (3x10)

T1 Bench: 72,5kg/160lbs (5x3)

T2 Bench: 50kg/110lbs (3x10)

T1 Deadlift: 125kg/275lbs (3x5)

T2 Deadlift: 85kg/187lbs (3x10)

Thanks! :)

summary: There are dozens of benefits to working out; it keeps your heart healthy for one, and has been proven to help you live longer....
caption: There are dozens of benefits to working out; it keeps your heart healthy for one, and has been proven to help you live longer. But sometimes you just want a workout that will burn calories fast, and we can also get behind that reasoning. Whether it’s to lose weight, fit into your favorite pair of jeans, or just feel more confident, we all have times when “calories burned” is the metric we’re most concerned with. So here you go: we’ve devised this quick 30-minute workout that burns 300 calories just like that!
